To solve the problem you have to understand that the framework creates an
object for each TestCase &#39;test&#39; method.  The idea is then to store information
about the file to execute while creating the TestCase instance (in the suite()
method).

One template can be:

import junit.framework.Test;
import junit.framework.TestCase;
import junit.framework.TestSuite;

public class BatchTest
        extends TestCase {

    String filename;

    public BatchTest( String name,
                      String filename ) {
        super( name );
        this.filename = filename;
    }

    public static Test suite() {
        TestSuite suite = new TestSuite();
        for ( int i = 0; i &lt; 10; i++ ) {
            suite.addTest( new BatchTest( &quot;testExecute&quot;, &quot;filename&quot; + i ));
        }
        return suite;
    }

    public void testExecute() {
        System.out.println( &quot;executing: &quot; + filename );
    }

}

Now every test is executed independently from the other and you will have (in
this case) 10 different tests executed.

Note that you cannot use the reflection but need to call BatchTest.suite()
explicitely.

Is it what you wanted?

